text: Can we make custom ads dynamic? Like hit an api on our end that does the roll based on something stored
I talked to tcgplayer today about perhaps dynamically hosting ads

attachments.fallback:
David Keatts commented on [medium] Report A Bug form: "this ended up being a lot more detailed than I anticipated, but I'm most of the way there

current architecture: <http://edhrec.com/bug-report|edhrec.com/bug-report> html form -> AWS api gateway -> lambda function -> ses forwarder -> email

we could've just used the edhrec api, but I was thinking "what if the api is bugged", plus it's a good opportunity for to check out what the api gateway has to offer.

the lambda function basically takes the data from the html form and builds an email (literally string concatenating header fields and such), then sends it off to ses.

as of now, I have emails making it all the way from the start to the end, but attachments (optional screenshot attachment) are coming out corrupted.  once I figure that out, I just need to add some client-side validation.

also, I'm very likely gonna add a similar "Contact Us" form in place of the "email us" link once this is all good."

attachments.fallback: David Keatts commented on [medium] Report A Bug form: "for most of today, all of my attachments were coming back corrupted, like the formatting was wrong.  I messed with a bunch of formatting options, then figured out it was because it was being interpreted as a json string.  I spent hours trying to switch the api gateway over to multipart/form-data, but could never get it to work.  then I learned that I could instead go back to json but base64 encode the attachment, and after reading some raw gmail output learned there's a header for auto-decoding base64 attachments.  so attachments are good now."
attachments.text: for most of today, all of my attachments were coming back corrupted, like the formatting was wrong.  I messed with a bunch of formatting options, then figured out it was because it was being interpreted as a json string.  I spent hours trying to switch the api gateway over to multipart/form-data, but could never get it to work.  then I learned that I could instead go back to json but base64 encode the attachment, and after reading some raw gmail output learned there's a header for auto-decoding base64 attachments.  so attachments are good now.
